tasks.prompt:
Construct explicitly a sequence of continuous functions f_n: [0,1] → [0,1] and a function f: [0,1] → ℝ such that:

(i) Each f_n is continuous on [0,1];
(ii) f_n(x) → f(x) for every x ∈ [0,1] (pointwise convergence everywhere);
(iii) f is NOT Riemann integrable on [0,1];
(iv) f IS Lebesgue integrable on [0,1] with respect to Lebesgue measure λ.

You must use the following explicit construction (or an equivalent one that you fully specify): Let C ⊂ [0,1] be a 'fat Cantor set' constructed by starting with [0,1] and, at stage n (n ≥ 1), removing from each of the 2^{n−1} remaining closed intervals the open middle subinterval of length 2^{−2n}. Let C_n denote the union of the 2^n closed intervals remaining after stage n. Define f_n(x) = max{0, 1 − 3^n · dist(x, C_n)} where dist(x, C_n) = inf{|x−y| : y ∈ C_n}.

Prove all four properties (i)–(iv) rigorously. For (iii), identify the set of discontinuities of f and prove it has positive Lebesgue measure. For (iv), compute the exact value of ∫_{[0,1]} f dλ.
